<doc id="980328" wikidata="Q5054344" url="?curid=980328" title="Cauchy space">
<text>In general topology and analysis, a Cauchy space is a generalization of metric spaces and uniform spaces for which the notion of Cauchy convergence still makes sense. Cauchy spaces were introduced by H. H. Keller in 1968, as an axiomatic tool derived from the idea of a Cauchy filter, in order to study completeness in topological spaces. The category of Cauchy spaces and &quot;Cauchy continuous maps&quot; is Cartesian closed, and contains the category of proximity spaces.

==Definition==

Throughout, formula_1 is a set, formula_2 denotes the power set of formula_3 and all filters are assumed to be proper/non-degenerate (i.e. a filter may not contain the empty set). 

A Cauchy space is a pair formula_4 consisting of a set formula_1 together a family formula_6 of (proper) filters on formula_1 having all of the following properties:
# For each formula_8 the discrete ultrafilter at formula_9 denoted by formula_10 is in formula_11
# If formula_12 formula_13 is a proper filter, and formula_14 is a subset of formula_15 then formula_16 
# If formula_17 and if each member of formula_14 intersects each member of formula_15 then formula_20 
An element of formula_21 is called a Cauchy filter, and a map formula_22 between Cauchy spaces formula_4 and formula_24 is Cauchy continuous if formula_25; that is, the image of each Cauchy filter in formula_1 is a Cauchy filter base in formula_27

==Properties and definitions==

Any Cauchy space is also a convergence space, where a filter formula_14 converges to formula_29 if formula_30 is Cauchy. In particular, a Cauchy space carries a natural topology.

==Examples==

* Any uniform space (hence any metric space, topological vector space, or topological group) is a Cauchy space; see Cauchy filter for definitions.
* A lattice-ordered group carries a natural Cauchy structure.
* Any directed set formula_31 may be made into a Cauchy space by declaring a filter formula_14 to be Cauchy if, given any element formula_33 there is an element formula_34 such that formula_35 is either a singleton or a subset of the tail formula_36 Then given any other Cauchy space formula_3 the Cauchy-continuous functions from formula_31 to formula_1 are the same as the Cauchy nets in formula_1 indexed by formula_41 If formula_1 is complete, then such a function may be extended to the completion of formula_43 which may be written formula_44 the value of the extension at formula_45 will be the limit of the net. In the case where formula_31 is the set formula_47 of natural numbers (so that a Cauchy net indexed by formula_31 is the same as a Cauchy sequence), then formula_31 receives the same Cauchy structure as the metric space formula_50 

==Category of Cauchy spaces==

The natural notion of morphism between Cauchy spaces is that of a Cauchy-continuous function, a concept that had earlier been studied for uniform spaces.

